1
00:00:12,169 --> 00:00:13,129
Well, hi everybody.

2
00:00:13,929 --> 00:00:15,710
We are the Beezark Company.

3
00:00:16,030 --> 00:00:20,691
We're located in Los Angeles, and I'm Adam Beezark, the company founder.

4
00:00:21,791 --> 00:00:23,772
I'm Lex Rhodes, I'm a creative coordinator.

5
00:00:24,892 --> 00:00:26,493
And I'm Vaughn Hannon, the creative technologist.

6
00:00:27,677 --> 00:00:31,840
And what we are not, is we are not a game developer.

7
00:00:32,200 --> 00:00:37,164
We're actually designers and producers of real-world attractions,

8
00:00:37,805 --> 00:00:46,372
spectacular rides, shows, and attractions for theme parks, museums, world's fairs, and big immersive experiences.

9
00:00:46,912 --> 00:01:02,197
And we've done a number of these, been involved in a lot of high-end projects around the world for folks like Disney and Universal, and for big museum experiences or visitor centers like Kennedy Space Center and Independence Hall in Philadelphia.

10
00:01:03,197 --> 00:01:09,082
And the reason we're here today is because even though we're in industries that are really very different,

11
00:01:09,582 --> 00:01:15,647
we keep finding that our world of physical experiences and your world of game design

12
00:01:16,267 --> 00:01:20,170
are much more closely related than we might have thought or that you may have realized.

13
00:01:20,750 --> 00:01:22,772
And that's what we'd like to talk about today.

14
00:01:23,613 --> 00:01:28,196
The relationship between gaming design and themed entertainment design.

15
00:01:28,656 --> 00:01:30,978
Because really, when it comes right down to it, we are all...

16
00:01:31,719 --> 00:01:40,382
Storytelling siblings. We're related closely. We are not identical twins. We're fraternal twins.

17
00:01:40,742 --> 00:01:44,344
There are similarities and differences, but that's kind of what we think is interesting

18
00:01:44,484 --> 00:01:49,746
to look into today because we think it will be of interest to you guys. So let's start off just

19
00:01:49,786 --> 00:01:54,948
by talking about what do we say when we talk about themed entertainment? What is it?

20
00:01:55,682 --> 00:01:58,544
Yeah, and theme entertainment is a big category.

21
00:01:58,584 --> 00:01:59,644
It's not just theme parks.

22
00:01:59,724 --> 00:02:02,246
It's not just the two big names that we hear a lot.

23
00:02:03,046 --> 00:02:06,408
It includes a whole range of immersive destination-based experiences.

24
00:02:07,592 --> 00:02:12,456
It's about placemaking, it's about transporting the guest, it's about escape, and those things

25
00:02:12,596 --> 00:02:13,917
probably sound a little familiar.

26
00:02:15,518 --> 00:02:19,501
And as we'll discuss in a little bit, there are things that are very theme entertainment

27
00:02:19,521 --> 00:02:21,122
and there are things that are very video game.

28
00:02:21,922 --> 00:02:26,426
And there's this weird land where things overlap and you end up with things like escape rooms

29
00:02:26,506 --> 00:02:28,687
and arcades with singing mice and pizza.

30
00:02:31,389 --> 00:02:36,413
That said, let's talk about where video games and themed entertainment have traditionally

31
00:02:36,473 --> 00:02:36,653
lived.

32
00:02:39,549 --> 00:02:48,458
Many years ago, Michael Eisner, who was then the head of Disney, drew this famous chart that has been used by entertainment designers for decades ever since.

33
00:02:48,838 --> 00:02:51,220
He sort of divided the world up into four kinds of entertainment.

34
00:02:51,641 --> 00:02:56,626
There is entertainment that people consume at home by themselves.

35
00:02:57,146 --> 00:03:00,930
There is entertainment you consume at home socially in a group.

36
00:03:01,791 --> 00:03:16,032
Then, out in the real world, outside your home, there's entertainment you consume alone at a destination, such as taking a walk in the forest, and there's entertainment that you consume in a group at a destination.

37
00:03:16,572 --> 00:03:20,154
And video games have always tended to occupy those first two squares

38
00:03:20,735 --> 00:03:24,617
because they tend to be based out of the home, unless you're at an arcade.

39
00:03:25,457 --> 00:03:31,300
And traditionally, theme parks have tended to occupy this sort of bottom right quadrant,

40
00:03:31,780 --> 00:03:34,502
the experiences that you have to leave your home for,

41
00:03:34,542 --> 00:03:37,183
but that you typically do with friends and family.

42
00:03:37,243 --> 00:03:41,406
So we tend to be about making memories with friends and family together.

43
00:03:41,726 --> 00:03:45,308
Today, obviously, those lines are blurring, and that's one of the things we find interesting.

44
00:03:46,733 --> 00:03:52,256
Yeah, home alone or otherwise, our two worlds have different strengths and weaknesses.

45
00:03:53,137 --> 00:03:56,899
And of course we all play to our strengths as often as we can, and we also embrace our limitations.

46
00:03:58,699 --> 00:04:02,341
Often we need to get a user from here to there. We know it, they know it.

47
00:04:03,142 --> 00:04:04,723
We put them on a track and wish them luck.

48
00:04:05,623 --> 00:04:12,406
Our job then is to surprise them and to hit them with all the tricks that we have to challenge and delight them.

49
00:04:17,187 --> 00:04:22,312
And that's why we want them to be surprising, but they are inevitable.

50
00:04:24,954 --> 00:04:29,298
And along the inevitable paths, among some of the surprises, we're going to make promises to the guests.

51
00:04:30,214 --> 00:04:34,836
And storytelling and world building is full of surprises and full of promises.

52
00:04:35,196 --> 00:04:39,779
And many of them are small and incidental, but some of them are big and wet.

53
00:04:40,539 --> 00:04:42,080
And the players have expectations.

54
00:04:43,221 --> 00:04:46,163
As our stories unfold, we are obligated to keep our promises.

55
00:04:46,643 --> 00:04:49,384
If we build a waterfall, there best be something behind it.

56
00:04:49,685 --> 00:04:53,207
By the way, that looks like a video game, but that's a real-world destination.

57
00:04:53,247 --> 00:04:56,428
That is Volcano Bay at Universal Studios, right?

58
00:04:58,647 --> 00:05:02,289
And it's really interesting to look at the histories of both of these different industries.

59
00:05:02,889 --> 00:05:06,350
A lot of the first theme park designers came from the world of animation.

60
00:05:06,410 --> 00:05:10,872
They were very much story first, designing media purely in service of story.

61
00:05:11,252 --> 00:05:15,594
And then you look at video games and you see an industry that arose very largely out of technology.

62
00:05:15,714 --> 00:05:18,955
And so you'd guess that theme parks would be designed stories first,

63
00:05:19,095 --> 00:05:21,516
games would be designed mechanics first, systems first.

64
00:05:22,036 --> 00:05:25,137
But everyone in this room knows that it's not quite so simple.

65
00:05:25,677 --> 00:05:26,938
You can even just take, for example,

66
00:05:27,369 --> 00:05:31,131
The case of two rides, Indiana Jones Adventure and Countdown to Extinction.

67
00:05:31,871 --> 00:05:36,673
For Indy, the Imagineers got to start with this story, this action archaeology adventure,

68
00:05:37,154 --> 00:05:42,296
and R&D goes and develops the perfect ride system to tell that story and to hit those emotional

69
00:05:42,337 --> 00:05:47,279
goals of, you know, what is Indiana Jones? And so they come up with the enhanced motion vehicles,

70
00:05:47,319 --> 00:05:51,742
the EMVs, and, you know, put those two together, it results in the ride that you know today.

71
00:05:52,317 --> 00:05:54,899
But for Countdown to Extinction, it was the other way around.

72
00:05:54,959 --> 00:05:59,283
They already had the EMVs and were tasked with skinning that ride system

73
00:05:59,363 --> 00:06:00,964
with this new dinosaur story.

74
00:06:01,345 --> 00:06:03,486
And it results in a much different ride.

75
00:06:05,228 --> 00:06:07,630
These are two industries that have a unique understanding

76
00:06:07,750 --> 00:06:10,712
of that interrelation between story and systems

77
00:06:10,853 --> 00:06:12,494
and trying to make them play nice together.

78
00:06:13,014 --> 00:06:17,258
It's a complicated and squiggly thing where every project is

79
00:06:17,278 --> 00:06:20,120
going to have different priorities and demand a slightly different process.

80
00:06:21,692 --> 00:06:28,456
So these worlds are pretty similar, and we have, over the years, learned a lot from each other,

81
00:06:28,656 --> 00:06:35,460
and we've borrowed from each other, and we figure it's not stealing, if you're related. It's learning.

82
00:06:35,981 --> 00:06:41,063
And so we're pretty interested in the things we can learn from the world of game design,

83
00:06:41,404 --> 00:06:44,746
and in some cases already have done to adapt ourselves into game design.

84
00:06:47,367 --> 00:06:50,469
We kind of use this word immersive.

85
00:06:51,653 --> 00:06:54,153
differently in our world than in game design.

86
00:06:55,254 --> 00:06:59,155
The game world talks about immersive in terms of getting in that flow state

87
00:06:59,195 --> 00:07:01,315
where you're so into the game that the rest of the world

88
00:07:01,595 --> 00:07:04,476
disappears and you sort of lose yourself in the rhythm of the gameplay.

89
00:07:04,996 --> 00:07:07,256
We literally mean immersion in a physical world.

90
00:07:07,537 --> 00:07:11,437
We mean designing spaces and scenery that creates a new space that is all around you

91
00:07:11,497 --> 00:07:12,838
and immersing you in it.

92
00:07:13,858 --> 00:07:14,938
And we talk about...

93
00:07:15,618 --> 00:07:22,741
Good show, in terms like good show and bad show, as being the things that keep you in that story or break the story for you.

94
00:07:23,541 --> 00:07:30,503
If it's bad show, if a trash can looks too modern, if you're in a period location.

95
00:07:30,823 --> 00:07:35,965
Those are things you guys deal with as well, but we have to deal with it in a physical world and move stuff around until it works.

96
00:07:37,346 --> 00:07:41,671
And in our world, immersion goes a long way back.

97
00:07:42,151 --> 00:07:45,615
Disney has been building immersion for decades.

98
00:07:45,875 --> 00:07:50,279
The Haunted Mansion ride, one of our favorite rides, was built over 50 years ago.

99
00:07:51,080 --> 00:07:57,967
And it created, it used a vehicle system that very carefully points each viewer at exactly what...

100
00:07:58,788 --> 00:08:03,011
The designers want you to see it functions as a movie camera in their eyes.

101
00:08:03,391 --> 00:08:09,977
But you could argue that it was arguably the very first ever first person camera controller, as if it was a game.

102
00:08:11,558 --> 00:08:17,323
And in modern gameplay, we use sticks to control our body and head motion.

103
00:08:17,443 --> 00:08:21,046
Disney was doing it with egg-shaped vehicles 50 years ago.

104
00:08:23,868 --> 00:08:26,070
And land design and level design are great.

105
00:08:26,580 --> 00:08:28,001
Very similar in many ways.

106
00:08:28,061 --> 00:08:32,405
They're all about providing environmental cues that support the story and provide tools

107
00:08:32,445 --> 00:08:34,346
for implicit navigation throughout.

108
00:08:35,167 --> 00:08:39,670
Here I pulled up maps of New Orleans Square at Disneyland and the Isle of Armor from Pokemon

109
00:08:39,690 --> 00:08:40,411
Sword and Shield.

110
00:08:40,831 --> 00:08:46,196
These make a nice comparison because they're both relatively self-contained spaces but

111
00:08:46,236 --> 00:08:47,697
freely explorable in 3D space.

112
00:08:49,177 --> 00:08:53,441
So when you make a land or a level for that matter, you always start with your main path.

113
00:08:54,162 --> 00:08:57,486
The purpose of this is to connect the major set pieces of the area.

114
00:08:58,327 --> 00:09:01,770
It's a relatively quick and expedient way of getting through the space,

115
00:09:02,191 --> 00:09:04,854
but it's also highly scenic since you have a lot of control,

116
00:09:05,294 --> 00:09:07,256
really tight control over the sight lines in this path.

117
00:09:08,371 --> 00:09:12,955
Then of course you have these ancillary detour paths that reward curiosity,

118
00:09:13,336 --> 00:09:17,439
allow you to investigate fun little nooks and cubbies just off of the main path.

119
00:09:17,920 --> 00:09:22,424
These paths let you stray a little bit, get a little bit lost, but they almost always,

120
00:09:22,444 --> 00:09:26,408
you can see here, they almost always loop back to the familiar, to the main path,

121
00:09:26,528 --> 00:09:29,771
rather than, you know, get you too uncomfortable.

122
00:09:30,051 --> 00:09:31,032
It's all about striking that

123
00:09:31,366 --> 00:09:35,829
Perfect amount, just the right amount of discomfort so that it feels exciting and adventurous.

124
00:09:36,389 --> 00:09:39,271
We sometimes talk about the idea of getting safely lost, right?

125
00:09:39,291 --> 00:09:43,234
You want to get just lost enough to get excited, but know you can always find your way back.

126
00:09:43,974 --> 00:09:47,856
And then even in these examples you can see they both have fast travel options.

127
00:09:47,917 --> 00:09:51,119
You've got the Disneyland Railroad, you've got the train, you've got flying options.

128
00:09:51,559 --> 00:09:55,942
And you have completely alternative locomotion options where you can actually take to the seas,

129
00:09:56,342 --> 00:09:59,684
cross the water, and pursue those far-off landmarks.

130
00:10:00,923 --> 00:10:05,046
There's another intuitive navigation tool that theme park designers specifically have

131
00:10:05,486 --> 00:10:07,588
a goofy word for, and that's weenies.

132
00:10:08,368 --> 00:10:13,492
A weenie is a large, eye-catching set piece, something like Sleeping Beauty Castle, that's

133
00:10:13,552 --> 00:10:17,875
visible from a great distance away, and it draws people through a space.

134
00:10:18,456 --> 00:10:22,959
Walt Disney coined the term describing how you can guide guests through space in the

135
00:10:22,999 --> 00:10:26,962
same way that he would lure his pet poodle from one room to the other with a hot dog.

136
00:10:29,195 --> 00:10:33,917
So if you've ever thought to yourself, wow, theme parks seem to have a lot of giant fake

137
00:10:33,957 --> 00:10:36,598
mountains in them, it's because they're excellent weenies.

138
00:10:37,338 --> 00:10:42,321
They're also really popular in games, partially for their use as a navigational tool, but

139
00:10:42,501 --> 00:10:47,583
also because that triangular shape is really excellent at concealing far off landmarks

140
00:10:47,623 --> 00:10:50,984
and then slowly revealing them as you move around the base of the mountain, which is

141
00:10:51,024 --> 00:10:51,385
really fun.

142
00:10:52,820 --> 00:10:58,904
So this kind of connection between placemaking and gameplay goes way, way, way back.

143
00:10:59,744 --> 00:11:06,308
If you go back as far as the 1893 Chicago World's Fair, the World's Columbian Exposition,

144
00:11:06,949 --> 00:11:16,855
one of the great sort of created events in American history, it was a world of different

145
00:11:16,895 --> 00:11:20,578
places from the very elegant to the very sort of folksy.

146
00:11:21,138 --> 00:11:29,382
But it also included some of the very first carnival games where you could actually step right up and take your chances and try to win a cupid doll.

147
00:11:30,283 --> 00:11:34,925
And over the years, theme parks have picked that up more and more.

148
00:11:35,546 --> 00:11:43,650
The very first bits of gameplay in theme park design started in the, arguably, in the 90s, I guess you could say.

149
00:11:43,890 --> 00:11:48,733
Disney did a terrific experiment in the 90s of a freestanding game.

150
00:11:49,534 --> 00:11:54,620
It was a location called Disney Quest that was filled with both off-the-shelf games,

151
00:11:54,640 --> 00:11:57,644
but also original games that they spent millions designing.

152
00:11:58,064 --> 00:12:02,790
And then, after building two of them, never built another one.

153
00:12:03,111 --> 00:12:08,878
But it led to a lot of other development in the sort of crossing over between game and theme parks.

154
00:12:09,158 --> 00:12:16,121
So in the theme park world, Disney installed a drive-thru shooting gallery.

155
00:12:16,721 --> 00:12:23,324
Disney installed, created an attraction shooting gallery, Buzz Lightyear's Astro Blasters,

156
00:12:23,364 --> 00:12:29,486
where you're fired at little green men. And since then, others have followed suit.

157
00:12:29,566 --> 00:12:33,208
The Six Flags parks have their Justice League Battle for Metropolis,

158
00:12:33,228 --> 00:12:35,208
which are very elaborate, where there's a combination of...

159
00:12:35,649 --> 00:12:38,330
Live media around you and shooting gallery.

160
00:12:38,731 --> 00:12:42,633
And just this month at Disney's California Adventure,

161
00:12:42,973 --> 00:12:48,237
the new Avengers Campus has an attraction called Web Slingers where you can fly with Spider-Man and

162
00:12:48,997 --> 00:12:52,279
without even any weapon in your hand, you can just use your hands to

163
00:12:52,540 --> 00:12:55,141
shoot webs at little robots that you're trying to catch.

164
00:12:56,942 --> 00:13:03,404
This kind of storytelling has broadened out and gameplay has taken on many different forms now in theme parks.

165
00:13:05,105 --> 00:13:10,507
These are using storytelling techniques from the world of RPGs and tabletop games.

166
00:13:12,007 --> 00:13:18,089
We're starting to see character-based storylines and quests that you can actually play as a guest in a park

167
00:13:18,589 --> 00:13:24,311
by interacting either with the environment or with live actors who are in character who are there for you to play with and talk to.

168
00:13:25,232 --> 00:13:31,736
Evermore Park in Utah is amazing. It's essentially an entire theme park that is a big D&D LARP game

169
00:13:32,016 --> 00:13:39,020
where you can take on a character, go on quests, meet wizards, and have experiences and challenges all day long

170
00:13:39,100 --> 00:13:43,803
and come back and they'll remember who you are and you can continue the quest you started the last time.

171
00:13:44,344 --> 00:13:50,550
These things aren't rides. These are real living worlds and story worlds where guests can have

172
00:13:50,710 --> 00:13:55,195
real agency and real input in the world really change and really make a difference.

173
00:13:56,036 --> 00:13:59,679
And some of the very biggest theme parks, Disney and Universal, are now

174
00:14:00,200 --> 00:14:05,704
Starting to include gaming layers that are deeply woven into the design of the entire land,

175
00:14:05,724 --> 00:14:09,367
where that actually affects the architecture and the rides and the pieces of the land,

176
00:14:09,767 --> 00:14:16,173
where you have special apps that you control or a wristband that you can let you play and interact with the land.

177
00:14:17,213 --> 00:14:20,596
And when we're doing that in big theme parks, it's happening.

178
00:14:21,407 --> 00:14:26,890
It has to happen at very high scale because you're handling tens of thousands of people a day through these things.

179
00:14:26,930 --> 00:14:32,273
So one of the big challenges is trying to figure out how to weave these into rides and live performance

180
00:14:32,494 --> 00:14:35,836
and these app layers and these little mini games that we go through.

181
00:14:36,296 --> 00:14:36,916
And it's not easy.

182
00:14:37,276 --> 00:14:42,199
So one of the things that we keep asking is, how can we make it even better?

183
00:14:42,719 --> 00:14:48,543
How can we steal more from each other and learn how to improve what we do by studying what you do and vice versa?

184
00:14:49,482 --> 00:14:55,307
Yeah, and earlier we alluded to the strengths and weaknesses in both of our industries,

185
00:14:55,407 --> 00:14:56,828
themed entertainment and video game design.

186
00:14:58,189 --> 00:15:07,516
You know, the big weaknesses in our world happen to be some of the best strengths in the video game world.

187
00:15:08,337 --> 00:15:13,761
We have a bunch of people together so we can do big spectacles and multi-sensory experiences,

188
00:15:13,981 --> 00:15:15,883
and they're highly social because everybody's in the same space.

189
00:15:17,084 --> 00:15:19,886
But it's really hard to do those individualized experiences,

190
00:15:21,347 --> 00:15:24,370
maintain persistence and progression and guest agency

191
00:15:24,410 --> 00:15:25,951
when you have to worry about things like Adam was saying,

192
00:15:25,991 --> 00:15:29,914
throughput and getting a million people through a space in an hour.

193
00:15:29,934 --> 00:15:35,179
Because that's what it boils down to in these physical spaces

194
00:15:35,259 --> 00:15:37,100
is throughput, throughput, throughput.

195
00:15:37,240 --> 00:15:38,301
How do we get all these people through

196
00:15:38,561 --> 00:15:41,224
and how do we get as many people into the experience as possible?

197
00:15:42,384 --> 00:15:47,046
So how do you, you know, is it possible to individualize those experiences?

198
00:15:48,087 --> 00:15:56,251
There's been attempts with VR and those offer very real headaches and also very operational headaches.

199
00:15:57,651 --> 00:16:01,593
And they actually don't individualize the experience all that much.

200
00:16:01,613 --> 00:16:04,194
Everybody's kind of doing the same thing.

201
00:16:04,214 --> 00:16:09,196
In a VR coaster, for example, you're all having the same experience.

202
00:16:09,857 --> 00:16:16,323
It might feel like it's individual to you, but everybody's experiencing the exact same thing.

203
00:16:17,044 --> 00:16:28,436
One of the best examples that I think provided individualization was Alien Encounter in Disney World in the Magic Kingdom,

204
00:16:29,697 --> 00:16:32,780
where you were in a theater, a round theater, and...

205
00:16:33,911 --> 00:16:40,586
If you haven't been on it, an alien shows up, gets loose, and then everybody has the experience of this alien's running around and it feels like it's right behind you.

206
00:16:40,606 --> 00:16:43,333
It's of course right behind everybody. You're all having that same experience again.

207
00:16:44,315 --> 00:16:47,476
But it feels very individual and extra terrifying.

208
00:16:48,517 --> 00:16:52,038
So, in that case, it was put everybody in the dark and just use audio,

209
00:16:52,098 --> 00:16:56,360
and shake their seats a little bit, and then you can have that experience.

210
00:16:56,420 --> 00:17:01,642
But it's a big challenge to individualize an experience

211
00:17:01,743 --> 00:17:04,444
in a place like a theme park or other destination.

212
00:17:06,044 --> 00:17:09,146
And I don't think we have it perfectly solved yet.

213
00:17:10,355 --> 00:17:12,762
You know, I think there's room for doing some more.

214
00:17:14,829 --> 00:17:21,091
Exploring guest versus guest type of experiences where, you know, things can be truly random.

215
00:17:21,152 --> 00:17:24,213
Even in video games, things aren't truly, you know, you have a very similar experience.

216
00:17:24,293 --> 00:17:28,194
Oh, I did this, I did this, I won this quest, I ran into this person, and I fought this boss.

217
00:17:29,334 --> 00:17:31,555
Oversimplified, but it's kind of the same thing, right?

218
00:17:31,575 --> 00:17:33,836
We're like, oh yeah, I did that, and this is how it went for me.

219
00:17:35,057 --> 00:17:38,938
So, things get truly random when you get into MMOs and you get other humans involved,

220
00:17:39,078 --> 00:17:43,380
and now you're like, oh, this last night, this crazy thing happened because so-and-so did this to me.

221
00:17:44,197 --> 00:17:49,201
and or challenge me to something and now you have all these new experiences that pop up that not

222
00:17:49,221 --> 00:17:54,686
everybody can have and then it's truly individual and I think we can get there.

223
00:17:57,288 --> 00:18:01,511
And then you've got other challenges like like persistence like in a video game you literally

224
00:18:01,551 --> 00:18:06,095
have a save file your progress is saved your individual impact on the world whether you're

225
00:18:06,115 --> 00:18:10,578
building things or destroying things that data gets stored and it carries over to the next time

226
00:18:10,618 --> 00:18:12,220
you visit that world but in a park.

227
00:18:12,940 --> 00:18:21,908
It's really hard to feel like you have an impact or a mark on that world, whether it's just in terms of story or literal environment, because it has to be scrubbed clean for the next guest.

228
00:18:22,008 --> 00:18:24,390
Everyone is expecting the same experience.

229
00:18:24,871 --> 00:18:30,195
And so it's really hard to figure out where are opportunities to give guests that feeling of persistence.

230
00:18:31,437 --> 00:18:34,900
Knott's Berry Farm has a seasonal immersive experience called Ghost Town Alive.

231
00:18:35,340 --> 00:18:39,146
where one of the really cool things that they do is they print an hourly newspaper.

232
00:18:39,446 --> 00:18:39,806
Oh yeah.

233
00:18:39,847 --> 00:18:44,192
So as guests, you know, they go on adventures, they have escapades throughout the area.

234
00:18:44,693 --> 00:18:49,480
Those are recorded, you know, whether good or bad, whether you're a hero or a bandit.

235
00:18:49,833 --> 00:18:53,894
Those are going to get recorded in the newspaper, and that's kind of, at least over the course of a day,

236
00:18:53,914 --> 00:18:57,915
maybe we could go for a longer time period in future experiences, but over the course of that day,

237
00:18:58,295 --> 00:19:02,796
you do see your impact on the world, and it's physically recorded in that space, which is pretty cool.

238
00:19:02,816 --> 00:19:04,916
You get to see your name in the paper and take that home with you.

239
00:19:04,936 --> 00:19:06,317
Yeah, and it's a great souvenir, too.

240
00:19:07,617 --> 00:19:09,677
Yeah, and along those lines, with persistence,

241
00:19:10,658 --> 00:19:17,919
it's kind of the same thing as how do you track progression for individuals in a park experience or in a location-based experience.

242
00:19:19,864 --> 00:19:25,385
It's a lot of times, you know, folks want to say that they want to gamify an experience,

243
00:19:25,805 --> 00:19:29,386
and I think a lot of us are like, oh, no.

244
00:19:29,747 --> 00:19:30,747
Another shooting gallery.

245
00:19:30,827 --> 00:19:31,747
Right, another shooting gallery.

246
00:19:31,767 --> 00:19:32,647
That's it.

247
00:19:32,908 --> 00:19:39,970
And, you know, they want all of the things from the video game world, but they don't.

248
00:19:40,714 --> 00:19:43,296
Then they realize how tricky that is and all those challenges that we're talking about.

249
00:19:43,376 --> 00:19:45,798
And then they're like, oh, never mind. Let's just make a shooting gallery.

250
00:19:46,518 --> 00:19:54,504
So, progression is also part of individualization where you want to be able to track your score.

251
00:19:54,545 --> 00:19:58,407
You want to be able to track your progress through whatever experiences you're having in the park.

252
00:19:58,788 --> 00:20:03,271
And it's starting to happen.

253
00:20:03,311 --> 00:20:05,513
It happened a little bit when Disney did Virtual Magic Kingdom.

254
00:20:06,033 --> 00:20:06,514
That opened in 2005.

255
00:20:06,554 --> 00:20:08,755
It was an online thing.

256
00:20:10,647 --> 00:20:11,588
It feels like a million years ago.

257
00:20:12,369 --> 00:20:16,693
But you could go to the parks and actually fulfill quests that would then give you digital

258
00:20:16,713 --> 00:20:18,074
goods in the Virtual Magic Kingdom.

259
00:20:18,554 --> 00:20:20,115
So you had a little bit of...

260
00:20:21,733 --> 00:20:27,355
It's a little bit of individualization, a little bit of progression, and you could go

261
00:20:27,395 --> 00:20:29,416
back and do another quest and get more stuff.

262
00:20:29,556 --> 00:20:33,818
And then those digital goods were only available to people who had done the things in the park,

263
00:20:33,838 --> 00:20:35,759
so you couldn't get them any other way, which is great.

264
00:20:36,779 --> 00:20:44,622
Super Nintendo World just opened in Universal in Osaka, and they built a secret game that

265
00:20:44,642 --> 00:20:45,883
you can only get to if you complete...

266
00:20:47,424 --> 00:20:53,148
If you find the five keys throughout the rest of the world, and they have... it's a watch.

267
00:20:53,884 --> 00:20:58,767
based on a watch-like wristband thing that keeps track of your progression so you know

268
00:20:58,787 --> 00:21:03,350
who got the five keys and you have to unlock the queue to this attraction by tapping your

269
00:21:03,510 --> 00:21:06,893
wrist. And then you can play the game that nobody else can play unless they've completed

270
00:21:06,913 --> 00:21:11,736
the thing. So there's a little bit happening there, being able to track your progress and

271
00:21:11,756 --> 00:21:17,079
do things. And then Disney again also did, of course, with Galaxy's Edge.

272
00:21:18,661 --> 00:21:24,324
You can use the app to start creating a little bit of a character for yourself

273
00:21:24,425 --> 00:21:29,348
and tracking your progress as that character and choose a side or be a scoundrel, which is the most fun.

274
00:21:34,216 --> 00:21:38,177
They've integrated that into the land really nicely so that there's multiple things to do.

275
00:21:38,977 --> 00:21:42,538
The attractions also tie into the game and into the app.

276
00:21:43,479 --> 00:21:47,080
So this stuff is starting to happen, but it's still a challenge.

277
00:21:47,140 --> 00:21:54,102
It's still tricky to provide this on the scale necessary for a park.

278
00:21:55,002 --> 00:21:57,823
I think one of the questions that we struggle with in the theme park world is

279
00:21:58,123 --> 00:21:59,883
we always want everybody to have a great time.

280
00:22:00,644 --> 00:22:03,706
Games are all about failing your way to success.

281
00:22:04,266 --> 00:22:04,486
So...

282
00:22:05,007 --> 00:22:05,627
Just like real life.

283
00:22:06,007 --> 00:22:06,208
Right?

284
00:22:06,948 --> 00:22:12,672
So, do you think it's possible for us to get to a place where there can be failure in a theme park?

285
00:22:13,032 --> 00:22:15,794
Or is that going to make little kids cry and parents unhappy?

286
00:22:16,775 --> 00:22:21,819
Yeah, it's a really interesting question, because failure can play so many different roles in games.

287
00:22:23,040 --> 00:22:25,822
There's, you know, using failure as stakes.

288
00:22:26,162 --> 00:22:30,165
When you play a game, when you're engaging with a game, you're kind of investing time and energy.

289
00:22:30,598 --> 00:22:35,399
in the name of advancement and progress, and failure kind of reclaims some of that progress

290
00:22:35,459 --> 00:22:36,479
and resets you a little bit.

291
00:22:37,060 --> 00:22:41,721
If you want to call it the threat of failure, it kind of adds a lot of tension and suspense

292
00:22:41,821 --> 00:22:43,301
to a gameplay experience.

293
00:22:43,541 --> 00:22:46,062
There's also failure as a proving ground.

294
00:22:46,142 --> 00:22:51,403
The idea that the harder something is to achieve, the better it's going to feel when you ultimately

295
00:22:51,443 --> 00:22:53,784
do win, after all those different attempts.

296
00:22:55,224 --> 00:23:04,046
Failure is comedy. Failure can actually be really funny, especially if you can create an environment where guests or players, they aren't shamed for messing up, but they're actually applauded.

297
00:23:04,167 --> 00:23:10,888
If you can reinforce that, failure can be really funny. And on top of all of that, failure can just be narratively interesting.

298
00:23:11,348 --> 00:23:21,951
If you make sure that you provide interesting narrative content, whether someone succeeds or fails, you know, there's just as much story to find at either end, then that's just branching narrative.

299
00:23:22,373 --> 00:23:25,775
And those are just two different interesting options that people can pursue.

300
00:23:27,315 --> 00:23:32,837
And obviously, some of these different uses of failure are more applicable to a parks environment than others.

301
00:23:33,537 --> 00:23:36,958
Really, it comes down to a problem of crowds and a problem of lines.

302
00:23:37,178 --> 00:23:44,580
Because when you don't have that instant reset, it makes it harder for it to be fun, to kind of re-tackle that challenge after suffering a failure.

303
00:23:46,586 --> 00:24:01,032
Yeah, and failure is part of one of the other big challenges that we have, which is guest agency, giving guests true choices and true freedoms to do things that affect their experiences and also affect the other things we've been talking about, persistence and progression.

304
00:24:03,052 --> 00:24:10,115
So, you know, giving users a choice makes a great experience, but we're limited by annoying things like physics and how much we can do.

305
00:24:10,975 --> 00:24:13,356
Curse you, laws of physics.

306
00:24:13,676 --> 00:24:15,397
So we haven't found our way around that yet.

307
00:24:15,925 --> 00:24:16,465
We're working on it.

308
00:24:17,445 --> 00:24:22,587
Our best efforts so far are kind of the illusion of agency, not real guest agency or not real

309
00:24:22,607 --> 00:24:23,927
player agency like you would have in a game.

310
00:24:26,368 --> 00:24:30,549
Like the wands in Diagon Alley, you feel like you, the individual, are having this experience

311
00:24:30,569 --> 00:24:35,411
and you, I'm sorry, the wizard, you the wizard are having this experience and causing something

312
00:24:35,431 --> 00:24:41,993
to happen, but it's you and the 20 wizards waiting in line behind you.

313
00:24:42,733 --> 00:24:47,137
watching the other wizard do work magic and then you wait for your turn to do the exact same magic.

314
00:24:47,157 --> 00:24:50,580
Exactly right, yes. And so that kind of takes a little bit of the magic out of it.

315
00:24:50,760 --> 00:25:00,769
And, you know, it's you choosing to affect the environment, but it's a very prefab version of guest agency.

316
00:25:00,869 --> 00:25:05,954
Right, and what in a single player game environment would be like a delightful little surprise that you stumble upon

317
00:25:06,034 --> 00:25:09,317
is now, it's not much different than a carnival game that you wait in line for.

318
00:25:09,918 --> 00:25:10,619
Right, exactly.

319
00:25:10,659 --> 00:25:15,064
So, we could go on about this stuff all day, but the other thing that we really wanted

320
00:25:15,104 --> 00:25:20,731
to cover with you guys is the connections, the professional connections between our worlds.

321
00:25:21,332 --> 00:25:26,358
That there's an awful lot of crossover between our business and the game design business.

